1 (5) Notwithstanding subsections (2) and (3) of this section, this section shall not restrict
2 any private electronic communications:
3 (a) Between a student and his or her family member who is a school district
4 employee or qualified school volunteer; or
5 (b) Between a student and a school district employee or qualified school
6 volunteer who reasonably believes an emergency exists that creates an
7 imminent risk to any person or property, provided the school district
8 employee promptly discloses the private electronic communication to his or
9 her immediate supervisor after the fact in accordance with subsection (6) of
10 this section.
11 (6) (a) A school district employee or qualified school volunteer that participated in
12 unauthorized electronic communication or reasonably believes[receives a
13 report alleging] that another school district employee or qualified school
14 volunteer participated in unauthorized electronic communication that has not
15 been previously reported shall immediately notify the supervising principal or
16 applicable supervisor. If the subject of the report is the principal or district-
17 wide employee, the reporting employee or volunteer shall immediately notify
18 the superintendent of the school district. If the subject of the report is the
19 superintendent or a Kentucky Department of Education employee assigned
20 to a school or area technology center within the school district, the reporting
21 employee or volunteer shall immediately notify the commissioner of
22 education and the chair of the local board of education.
23 (b) A school district employee that violates paragraph (a) of this subsection
24 may[shall] be subject to disciplinary action in accordance with:
25 1. For certified employees, KRS 161.120 and 161.790; or
26 2. For classified employees, KRS 161.011(7).
27 (7) (a) Upon receipt of a report alleging that a school district employee or qualified
Page 6 of 8
SB018110.100 - 175 - XXXX 1/27/2026 4:38 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 181/GA
1 school volunteer participated in unauthorized electronic communication, the
2 commissioner of education, a principal, or a superintendent shall immediately:
3 1. Notify the parent of each student that is an alleged party to the
4 unauthorized electronic communications; and
5 2. a. If the individual that is the subject of the report is a certified
6 employee:
7 i. Notify the Education Professional Standards Board, which
8 shall promptly investigate all allegations received under this
9 subsection and proceed with appropriate disciplinary actions
10 in accordance with KRS 161.120; and
11 ii. Investigate the underlying allegations and proceed with
12 appropriate disciplinary actions in accordance with KRS
13 161.790;
14 b. If the individual that is the subject of the report is a classified
15 employee, investigate the underlying allegations and proceed with
16 appropriate disciplinary actions in accordance with KRS
17 161.011(7);[ and]
18 c. If the individual that is the subject of the report is a qualified
19 school[ or district] volunteer, the school or district shall investigate
20 the underlying allegations and, if substantiated, the qualified
21 school volunteer may[shall] be prohibited from future school and
22 district volunteer opportunities; and
23 d. Notwithstanding any statute to the contrary, notify the parent of
24 each student that is an alleged party to the unauthorized
25 electronic communication of each material phase of an
26 investigation and disciplinary action under this subparagraph,
27 including but not limited to a written summary of the results of
Page 7 of 8
SB018110.100 - 175 - XXXX 1/27/2026 4:38 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 181/GA
1 an investigation and the final outcome of the disciplinary action.
2 (b) A principal or superintendent who violates paragraph (a) of this subsection
3 shall be subject to disciplinary action in accordance with KRS 156.132 and
4 161.120.
5 Section 2. If a school district volunteer was prohibited from future school
6 volunteer opportunities pursuant to subsection (3)(c) of Section 1 of this Act prior to the
7 effective date of this Act, a school district may permit that person to participate in future
8 school volunteer opportunities.
9 Section 3. Whereas it is critical to ensure that parents, schools, and school
10 districts have clarity on lawful electronic communication with students, an emergency is
11 declared to exist, this Act takes effect upon its passage and approval by the Governor or
12 upon its otherwise becoming a law.
